### Command-Line Linting and Formatting Commands

Source: https://hk.jdx.dev/builtins.html

A collection of CLI commands used for checking and fixing various file types across the project, including TOML, YAML, XML, and source code files.

```bash
# Formatting TOML
tombi format --check --diff {{ files }}
tombi format {{ files }}

# Trailing Whitespace
hk util trailing-whitespace --diff {{files}}
hk util trailing-whitespace --fix {{files}}

# TypeScript/JavaScript
tsc --noEmit -p {{workspace_indicator}}
xo --fix {{ files }}

# YAML/OpenAPI
vacuum lint --fix {{files}}
yamlfmt -lint {{ files }}
yamllint --strict {{ files }}
yq -iP {{ files }}

# Security/Linting
zizmor --no-progress --fix {{ files }}

# Spelling
typos --force-exclude --write-changes {{ files }}
```

--------------------------------

### Format JSON with jq

Source: https://hk.jdx.dev/builtins.html

Checks and formats JSON files using jq. It ensures JSON is pretty-printed and can detect formatting errors.

```shell
failed=0
for f in {{ files }};
  do jq . "$f" | diff -u "$f" - || failed=1
done
exit $failed
```

```shell
for f in {{ files }};
  do tmp=$(mktemp) && jq -S . "$f" > "$tmp" && mv "$tmp" "$f"
done
```

### Configuration > hk.pkl > Example

Source: https://hk.jdx.dev/configuration.html

Here's a basic `hk.pkl` file:
amends "package://github.com/jdx/hk/releases/download/v1.38.0/hk@1.38.0#/Config.pkl"
import "package://github.com/jdx/hk/releases/download/v1.38.0/hk@1.38.0#/Builtins.pkl"

local linters = new Mapping<String, Step> {
    // linters can be manually defined
    ["eslint"] {
        // the files to run the linter on, if no files are matched, the linter will be skipped
        // this will filter the staged files and return the subset matching these globs
        glob = List("*.js", "*.ts")
        // the command to run that makes no changes
        check = "eslint {{files}}"
        // the command to run that fixes the files (used by default)
        fix = "eslint --fix {{files}}"
        // optional: files matching these globs will be staged after fix modifies them
        // defaults to the step's glob when staging is enabled, so usually not needed
        // stage = List("*.js", "*.ts")
    }
    // linters can also be specified with the Builtins pkl library
    ["prettier"] = Builtins.prettier
}

hooks {
    ["pre-commit"] {
        fix = true       // runs the fix step to make modifications
        stash = "git"    // stashes unstaged changes before running fix steps
        steps = linters
    }
    ["pre-push"] {
        steps = linters
    }
    // "fix" and "check" are special steps for `hk fix` and `hk check` commands
    ["fix"] {
        fix = true
        steps = linters
    }
    ["check"] {
        steps = linters
        // optional: run a report after the hook finishes; HK_REPORT_JSON contains timing JSON
        report = #"node scripts/upload-timings.js <<<"$HK_REPORT_JSON""
    }
}

The first line (`amends`) is critical because that imports the base configuration pkl for extending.

--------------------------------

### Hooks > <HOOK>.steps > <STEP>.check

Source: https://hk.jdx.dev/configuration.html

The check property defines a command that performs validation without modifying files, such as running a linter in check mode. Because these commands do not alter the filesystem, they are ideal for parallel execution. The check command supports template variables like {{files}} to receive the list of target files, and can be configured as a Script to provide platform-specific command variations for Linux, macOS, and Windows.

--------------------------------

### Hooks

Source: https://hk.jdx.dev/hooks.html

Each linter provides a "check" and "fix" commands. "check" commands are read-only and can be run in parallel. "fix" commands can edit files and will block other "fix" or "check" commands from running at the same time. Note that hk does not enforce that "check" commands do not write to files for performance reasons however you still should try to follow this convention in order for hk to behave as expected. It's the read/write locking behavior that hk makes use of in order to run hooks as fast as possible while still being safe.

